'''Campo Santo''' (Latin, ''[[campus sanctus]]'', "holy field") is an Italian and Spanish name for a burial-place or [[cemetery]]. 

The term derives from the Campo Santo at Pisa, the name given to a novel city initiative begun in the thirteenth century, which led to the formal design and laying-out of Europe's first medieval extra-mural burial ground or cemetery (i.e. a place of general burial separate from a church and its churchyard). The idea was not taken up widely elsewhere in Europe until after the Reformation, when several further extra-mural burial grounds or early cemeteries became established, e.g. at Geneva and in German principalities. However, the principal impetus came much later - in the early nineteenth century - when, following the fashionable example set by Pere la Chaise in Paris as an attractively landscaped and spacious garden cemetery, and the widespread perception of many city authorities that it was becoming necessary on hygiene grounds to close overfull city churchyards and crypts, a wide range of garden cemeteries, rural cemeteries, woodland cemeteries and monumental cemeteries became laid out in Europe and North America.  Increasingly these were designed with their own chapels, or chapels became added, and the full range of modern cemetery designs emerged.

